## Verified: gap is closed by Lemma `lem:chi-min`.

The current `solution.tex` contains a complete proof of well-definedness exactly as requested. Lemma `lem:chi-min` establishes, for fixed $H$ and $\mathcal A_H=\{K\mid K\to H\}$:
1. $H\in\mathcal A_H$ (reflexivity of the partial order $\to$);
2. pairwise intersection-closure: if $K_1\to H,K_2\to H$, then axiom (1) gives $K_2\subseteq H$, restriction axiom (3) with $J=K_2$ gives $K_1\cap K_2\to K_2$, and transitivity with $K_2\to H$ gives $K_1\cap K_2\to H$;
3. finite intersection-closure by induction;
4. since $\mathrm{Sub}(G)$ is finite, $K_\ast:=\bigcap_{K\to H}K\in\mathcal A_H$ and is the least element, so $\min\{K\mid K\to H\}$ is attained, equals $\bigcap_{K\to H}K$, and $\chi^{\mathcal O}(H)\to H$.

The immediately following paragraph records that $\chi^{\mathcal O}(H)\to H$ (used downstream, e.g. in Lemma `lem:geom`) and $\chi^{\mathcal O}(H)\subseteq H$.

I independently re-verified the load-bearing claim numerically: for $C_4$, $S_3$, and $D_4$, generating many valid transfer systems (closing random seeds under reflexivity, conjugation-invariance, transitivity, and the restriction axiom, with antisymmetry checked), in every case $\mathcal A_H$ is closed under intersection, the total intersection lies in $\mathcal A_H$, and it is related into $H$. All checks passed.

No change to `solution.tex` was necessary; the one-line lemma the human requested is present and correct. Resolving.
